diagnoses.name: Chronic sinusitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation and swelling of the sinuses, leading to congestion, which can cause difficulty swallowing (dysphagia) due to postnasal drip.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth, which can contribute to dysphagia and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: A disease involving abnormal collections of inflammatory cells that can form as nodules in multiple organs, causing fibrosis, lymphadenopathy, and dyspnea.

diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including lymphadenopathy, fibrosis, and possibly dysmenorrhea.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that begins in the lymphatic system, leading to lymphadenopathy, and it can affect various organs, contributing to dysphagia.

diagnoses.name: Endometriosis
diagnoses.description: A disorder in which tissue similar to the tissue that normally lines the inside of the uterus grows outside it, causing severe dysmenorrhea and potentially leading to fibrosis.

diagnoses.name: Thyroiditis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the thyroid gland, which can cause dysphagia due to the gland's location and might be associated with fibrosis in chronic cases.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. While not directly causing the listed symptoms, its associated conditions could.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease that primarily affects the lungs but can affect other parts of the body, causing lymphadenopathy, fibrosis, and potentially dysphagia if involving the lymph nodes of the neck.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A digestive disorder that affects the lower esophageal sphincter, leading to acid reflux which can cause dysphagia.

diagnoses: Dermatologic Conditions Related to Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome
Diabetes Mellitus – considering the presence of hyperglycemia.
Chronic Kidney Disease – potential cause of hyperglycemia, leukopenia (due to compromised immune system), and could contribute to gastroesophageal reflux.
Autoimmune Disorders (e.g., Lupus) – can cause leukopenia, easy bleeding, and potentially interstitial cystitis.
Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD) – directly related to gastroesophageal reflux symptoms.
Interstitial Cystitis – as a primary diagnosis for bladder pain and urinary symptoms.
Leukemia – could explain easy bleeding and leukopenia.
Immune Thrombocytopenic Purpura (ITP) – could cause easy bleeding.
Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome – can cause gastroesophageal reflux due to increased acid production, and could indirectly affect blood glucose levels.
Von Willebrand Disease – a possible cause for easy bleeding.
HIV/AIDS – could be a cause of leukopenia and indirectly affect other systems already compromised, contributing to conditions like interstitial cystitis or hyperglycemia.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests
diagnoses: Asthma (considering wheezing, and dyspnea; normal pulmonary function tests can sometimes occur outside of an acute episode)
Irritable bowel syndrome (considering diarrhea; can sometimes be associated with other systemic symptoms)
Eosinophilic gastroenteritis (considering diarrhea, wheezing, dyspnea due to eosinophilic infiltration; may not always show on pulmonary function tests)
Churg-Strauss syndrome (eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis - considering asthma symptoms, eosinophilia, possible skin manifestations like dyshidrotic eczema)
Ankylosing spondylitis (considering chronic back pain, can also have lung involvement but less commonly associated with diarrhea or skin manifestations)
Food allergy (considering diarrhea and possible atopic dermatitis, which could present similarly to dyshidrotic eczema; may also have respiratory symptoms)
Chronic pancreatitis (considering chronic back pain, diarrhea; less directly related to respiratory symptoms, but can have associated nutritional deficiencies affecting overall health)
Celiac disease (considering diarrhea; can have dermatitis herpetiformis which can be confused with eczema, and may present with respiratory symptoms in rare instances)
Inflammatory bowel disease (Crohn's disease or ulcerative colitis - considering diarrhea, can have associated arthritic back pain, skin lesions similar to eczema, and rare lung involvement)
Hypereosinophilic syndrome (considering wheezing, dyspnea, diarrhea due to eosinophil infiltration in various organs, skin manifestations)

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones.
common_symptoms: pain, stiffness or swelling in your joints
heavier than normal or irregular menstrual periods

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues, causing fatigue and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions in which your immune system mistakenly attacks your body. Both hypothyroidism and interstitial cystitis can be related to autoimmune conditions.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition.
common_symptoms: enlarged lymph nodes in your neck or armpits

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when you use or lose more fluid than you take in, and your body doesn't have enough water and other fluids to carry out its normal functions.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when the body does not get or is unable to absorb the amount of vitamin B12 it needs, which can lead to anemia and neurological issues.
common_symptoms: soreness of the mouth or tongue

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the marrow to make too many red blood cells, which thickens the blood, slowing its flow.
common_symptoms: itchiness, especially after a warm bath or shower

diagnoses.name: Pheochromocytoma
diagnoses.description: A rare, usually benign tumor that develops in an adrenal gland, which can cause high blood pressure, headaches, palpitations, and symptoms of anxiety.

diagnoses.name: Mitral Valve Prolapse
diagnoses.description: A condition in which two valve flaps of the mitral valve do not close smoothly or evenly, but bulge (prolapse) upward into the left atrium, sometimes causing palpitations.

diagnoses.name: Cardiac Arrhythmias
diagnoses.description: Conditions that cause irregular heartbeats. Symptoms can include palpitations among others.

diagnoses: Pediatric Autoimmune Neuropsychiatric Disorders Associated with Streptococcal Infections (PANDAS)

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests
diagnoses: Heart diseases (e.g., heart failure can cause dyspnea and anxiety)
Sleep disorders (e.g., obstructive sleep apnea, despite normal pulmonary function tests, can cause non-restorative sleep and daytime fatigue)
Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (considering dyspnea; however, might not align with 'normal pulmonary function tests')
Restless legs syndrome (can cause non-restorative sleep and is associated with iron dysregulation)
Mental health disorders, including depression (overlap with anxiety and sleep disturbance)
Thyroid disorders (hyperthyroidism can cause anxiety, dyspnea, and sleep disturbances)
Inflammatory Bowel Disease (Crohn's disease and Ulcerative Colitis)
Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms (DRESS)
Urinary tract infection (in the context of incontinence specifically)
Inflammatory bowel disease (Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis)
Anaphylactoid reaction (including reactions to drugs or contrast agents)
Mast cell disorders (such as systemic mastocytosis)

diagnoses.name: Migraine with aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by severe head pain accompanied by visual disturbances, numbness, and sensitivity to sound (phonophobia).

diagnoses.name: Migraine without aura
diagnoses.description: A chronic disorder characterized by recurrent moderate to severe headaches often in association with a number of autonomic nervous system symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Tension-type headache
diagnoses.description: A common type of headache characterized by a constant ache or pressure around the head, especially at the temples or back of the head and neck.

diagnoses.name: Cluster headache
diagnoses.description: A neurological disorder characterized by recurrent, severe headaches on one side of the head, typically around the eye.

diagnoses.name: Transient ischemic attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it's a brief period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke, such as weakness and numbness, which do not last long and do not cause lasting damage.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system that disrupts the flow of information within the brain, and between the brain and body. It can cause numbness, weakness, and other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Symptoms can include headache, numbness, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Depending upon the location and size, it can cause headache, weakness, numbness, and other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness.

diagnoses.name: Anaemia
diagnoses.description: A condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues, causing potential weakness, fatigue, and other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by severe head pain followed or accompanied by sensory disturbances such as flashes of light, blind spots, tingling in the arms and legs, nausea, vomiting, and increased sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Migraine without Aura
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms including but not limited to severe, debilitating headaches, sensitivity to light and sound, nausea, and vomiting. Lacks the sensory disturbances that define aura.

diagnoses.name: Tension-Type Headache
diagnoses.description: A common type of headache characterized by a dull, aching pain sensation encompassing the head with symptoms such as sensitivity to light and sound, but generally lacking the severe nature of migraines.

diagnoses.name: Cluster Headaches
diagnoses.description: Severe, recurrent headaches on one side of the head, often around the eye, with possible redness and tearing in the eye, stuffy nose, and forehead and facial sweating.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. It can include weakness, speech disturbance, and loss of vision or double vision.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system marked by numbness, weakness, the loss of muscle coordination, and problems with vision, speech, and bladder control.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Abnormal growth of cells within the brain that can cause symptoms such as headache, weakness, seizures, difficulty speaking, and visual changes.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by high pressure inside the skull without any detectable cause. Symptoms often resemble those of a brain tumor.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An infection of the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, known as the meninges. It can lead to headaches, fever, and a stiff neck.

diagnoses.name: Post-Traumatic Headache
diagnoses.description: Headache occurring after head injury, often accompanied by other symptoms such as dizziness, insomnia, concentration difficulties, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that is often accompanied by visual disturbances (scintillation) and sensitivity to sound (phonophobia). Nausea and vomiting can also occur.
diagnoses.treatment: Treatment may include medications for pain relief and prevention, as well as lifestyle changes to avoid triggers.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing vertigo, hearing loss, tinnitus, and a feeling of fullness or congestion in the ear. Nausea and vomiting can also occur as a result of vertigo.
diagnoses.treatment: Management includes dietary changes, medications to control vertigo and nausea, and in some cases, surgery.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that may cause vertigo, dizziness, and imbalance, in addition to or instead of the more typical migraine symptoms. Phonophobia and scintillation may also occur.
diagnoses.treatment: Treatment can include medications used for traditional migraines, as well as vestibular rehabilitation exercises.

diagnoses.name: Motion Sickness
diagnoses.description: A condition in which a disagreement exists between visually perceived movement and the vestibular system's sense of movement, resulting in symptoms like nausea, vomiting, and vertigo.
diagnoses.treatment: Prevention and treatment include over-the-counter and prescription medications, as well as behavior modifications.

diagnoses.name: Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV)
diagnoses.description: A disorder arising from a problem in the inner ear, characterized by short episodes of vertigo in relation to changes in the position of the head, with possible nausea.
diagnoses.treatment: The Epley maneuver or other similar canalith repositioning procedures are typically effective.

diagnoses.name: Gastroenteritis
diagnoses.description: An infection of the gut that can cause vomiting and nausea along with diarrhea. Vertigo may occur due to dehydration.
diagnoses.treatment: Treatment focuses on staying hydrated and rested. In some cases, medication may be necessary.

diagnoses.name: Labyrinthitis
diagnoses.description: An inner ear infection that can cause vertigo, hearing loss, and symptoms such as nausea and vomiting.
diagnoses.treatment: Treatment usually involves medications to relieve symptoms, including corticosteroids and antiviral drugs, depending on the cause.

diagnoses.name: Concussion
diagnoses.description: A traumatic brain injury that can cause headaches, symptoms including nausea, vomiting, vertigo, and sensitivity to light or sound.
diagnoses.treatment: Management generally includes rest and gradually returning to normal activities while being monitored for symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Depending on its location, it can cause nausea, vomiting, headaches, and potentially symptoms like phonophobia due to increased intracranial pressure.
diagnoses.treatment: Treatment options can include surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Ingestion
diagnoses.description: Consumption of toxic substances can lead to nausea, vomiting, dizziness, vertigo, and other systemic symptoms.
diagnoses.treatment: Treatment involves eliminating the toxin from the body and supportive care to manage symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: Migraine headaches can cause severe throbbing pain or a pulsing sensation, usually on one side of the head. It's often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound. Migraine attacks can cause significant pain for hours to days and can be so severe that the pain is disabling.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.details: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers and causes communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes
diagnoses.details: In diabetes, elevated blood sugar levels can lead to a variety of complications, including nerve damage (diabetic neuropathy) that can cause weakness and numbness typically in the hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.details: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. A stroke is a medical emergency that can cause paralysis, numbness, and cognitive difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: Anemia, a condition characterized by a lack of healthy red blood cells, can lead to feelings of weakness and fatigue. While less commonly directly linked to headache and numbness, severe anemia can exacerbate these symptoms due to decreased oxygen delivery to tissues.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.details: Meningitis is an inflammation of the membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. The swelling from meningitis typically triggers symptoms such as headache, fever, and a stiff neck.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.details: Lyme disease is a bacterial infection you get from the bite of an infected tick. The early stage of the infection can cause headaches and weakness, and if not treated, it can lead to neurological problems, including numbness.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.details: Brain tumors can press on nerve cells in the brain. This pressure can cause headaches and weakness, among other symptoms. As the tumor grows, it can affect the brain's ability to process sensory information, leading to numbness.

diagnoses.name: Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.details: Peripheral neuropathy refers to the conditions that result when nerves that carry messages to and from the brain and spinal cord from and to the rest of the body are damaged or diseased. This can cause weakness, numbness, and pain, usually in the hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.details: Anxiety disorders can physically manifest through various symptoms, including muscle weakness, headaches, and even numbness. These physical symptoms can stem from the body's fight-or-flight response, which prepares the body to either confront or avoid a perceived threat.

diagnoses: Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (formerly known as Wegener's granulomatosis)
